1
00:00:01,229 --> 00:00:09,635
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:10,087 --> 00:00:32,787
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,412 --> 00:01:03,281
Now in the next passage that Bhikkhu Bodhi has chosen, The Quest for Enlightenment, there are one or two discourses, well there's a few actually, that describe what happened on his journey to become enlightened, and they're all slightly different, but generally speaking,

4
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:21,445
The thing was he went to these two teachers who taught him how to do the absorption states, then something like two years, and then he spent four years doing these very hard self-mortification exercises, and then he became liberated.

5
00:01:22,927 --> 00:01:29,977
But here in this one, you see, it doesn't mention the fact that he went off and did these self-mortification exercises.

6
00:01:30,903 --> 00:01:33,566
But it does tell us at the beginning why he left home.

7
00:01:35,810 --> 00:01:39,534
Amongst there are two kinds of search, the noble and the ignoble search.

8
00:01:41,378 --> 00:01:42,739
And what is the ignoble search?

9
00:01:42,799 --> 00:01:48,828
Here, someone, being himself subject to birth, seeks what is also subject to birth.

10
00:01:49,569 --> 00:01:53,215
Being subject to ageing, seeks also what is subject to ageing.

11
00:01:53,855 --> 00:01:57,501
And being subject to sickness, he seeks also what is subject to sickness.

12
00:02:01,007 --> 00:02:04,135
And being subject to death, he seeks also what is subject to death.

13
00:02:04,215 --> 00:02:09,127
Being subject to sorrow, he seeks something which is subject to sorrow.

14
00:02:09,187 --> 00:02:13,979
And being subject to defilement, he seeks what is subject to defilement.

15
00:02:13,998 --> 00:02:18,408
So remember that one of his big awakening moments

16
00:02:18,759 --> 00:02:23,389
was the realisation that, you know, sickness old, there's sickness, ageing and death.

17
00:02:24,110 --> 00:02:27,557
And, you know, like the comedian says, life's hard and then you die.

18
00:02:29,461 --> 00:02:40,144
So that was one of his reasons for leaving the lay life, the life of the householder, as it's put usually here, you see.

19
00:02:40,933 --> 00:02:46,424
But seeking himself subject to sorrow, seeks what is also subject to sorrow.

20
00:02:47,425 --> 00:02:51,072
So that again comes back to the idea of impermanence.

21
00:02:51,092 --> 00:02:54,679
So, you know, the loss of someone you love, you see.

22
00:02:54,899 --> 00:02:59,287
So you're seeking something which eventually is going to bring you sorrow.

23
00:03:00,027 --> 00:03:03,735
Subject to defilement, he seeks also something subject to defilement.

24
00:03:04,205 --> 00:03:10,995
So that can range from anything which forms an attachment like pleasures to something illegal and horrible.

25
00:03:13,018 --> 00:03:23,332
So having stated his ground, you see, he then says, And what may be subject to birth, aging, sickness and death, to sorrow and defilement?

26
00:03:24,394 --> 00:03:25,336
Wife and children.

27
00:03:25,536 --> 00:03:26,296
Remember, he's a bloke.

28
00:03:28,301 --> 00:03:31,085
So obviously for a woman it's a husband and children.

29
00:03:31,665 --> 00:03:33,087
Men and women slaves.

30
00:03:33,907 --> 00:03:37,492
So remember all ancient societies had slaves in one way or the other.

31
00:03:38,252 --> 00:03:40,937
It didn't really move very much in the medieval ages either.

32
00:03:41,516 --> 00:03:44,841
The word serf comes from the Latin servus which meant slaves.

33
00:03:46,143 --> 00:03:49,165
We now have servants and serving.

34
00:03:49,687 --> 00:03:56,014
Goats and sheep, fowl and pigs, elephants, cattle, horses and mares, gold and silver.

35
00:03:56,872 --> 00:04:16,670
These acquisitions are subject to birth, aging, sickness and death, to sorrow and defilement, and one who is tied to these things, infatuated with them and utterly absorbed in them, being himself subject to birth, to sorrow and defilement, seeks what is also subject to birth, aging and death, to sorrow and defilement.

36
00:04:16,690 --> 00:04:26,759
So now, whenever I read something like this out, and of course, in the story of the Buddha leaving the lay life, and the fact that after he was fully liberated, he didn't go back,

37
00:04:27,060 --> 00:04:56,646
there's a tendency to think that the Buddha had a real downer on lay life but remember you see you have to read it slightly carefully because he doesn't say that he says tied to these things infatuated with them utterly absorbed in them that's the problem remember the problem is our relationship to the life that we're living and the usual sort of question that comes up is you know is it better to become a monastic

38
00:04:56,997 --> 00:04:59,721
in order to achieve full liberation.

39
00:05:00,041 --> 00:05:01,745
Well, ideally speaking, no.

40
00:05:02,065 --> 00:05:10,240
One is either drawn to an institutional form of the spiritual life or a non-institutional form.

41
00:05:10,261 --> 00:05:12,625
An institution is defined by its rules and regulations.

42
00:05:13,365 --> 00:05:15,529
So there's a lay institution.

43
00:05:16,853 --> 00:05:21,620
Before he died, he said he was quite happy because the four assemblies had been established.

44
00:05:22,072 --> 00:05:25,279
the monks and the nuns, the lay women and the lay men.

45
00:05:25,781 --> 00:05:27,745
He called them the four assemblies.

46
00:05:27,766 --> 00:05:31,213
And he felt that these were now grounded and established and he was happy for them.

47
00:05:32,076 --> 00:05:35,523
And for each of these he established a certain rule.

48
00:05:35,783 --> 00:05:38,529
So the rule of the nuns was slightly different from the monks.

49
00:05:39,353 --> 00:05:43,298
and the rule for men and women were generally the same.

50
00:05:44,218 --> 00:05:50,386
But even so, as you read the scriptures, there are different advice given to both.

51
00:05:50,807 --> 00:05:56,333
But generally speaking, it's the same sila, the same five precepts.

52
00:05:58,696 --> 00:06:01,259
So you have to be careful when you read this sort of stuff.

53
00:06:01,278 --> 00:06:06,846
The Buddha's now got a downer on the lay life.

54
00:06:08,918 --> 00:06:12,107
So then he says, so what is the noble search?

55
00:06:12,367 --> 00:06:23,822
Well, it's someone being self-subject to birth, having understood the danger of what is subject to birth, seeks the unborn supreme security from bondage, Nibbana.

56
00:06:24,324 --> 00:06:34,096
Being himself subject to aging, having understood the danger in what is subject to aging, he seeks the unaging supreme security from bondage, nibbana.

57
00:06:34,896 --> 00:06:46,670
And being himself subject to sickness, having understood the danger in what is subject to sickness, he seeks the unailing supreme security from bondage, nibbana.

58
00:06:46,651 --> 00:06:58,208
Being himself subject to death, having understood the danger in what is subject to death, he seeks the deathless supreme security from bondage, Nibbana.

59
00:07:00,690 --> 00:07:10,384
Being himself subject to sorrow, having understood the danger in what is subject to sorrow, he seeks the sorrowless supreme security from bondage, Nibbana.

60
00:07:10,404 --> 00:07:13,569
And being himself subject to defilement, having understood the

61
00:07:13,853 --> 00:07:16,055
the danger in what is subject to defilement.

62
00:07:16,396 --> 00:07:20,641
He seeks the undefiled supreme security from bondage, Nibbana.

63
00:07:20,661 --> 00:07:21,742
This is the noble search.

64
00:07:22,444 --> 00:07:28,230
And often you'll see in the discourses that's exactly how he describes Nibbana.

65
00:07:28,490 --> 00:07:30,413
It's unborn.

66
00:07:32,456 --> 00:07:33,557
It's unaging.

67
00:07:35,920 --> 00:07:36,742
It's unailing.

68
00:07:38,903 --> 00:07:39,805
It is the deathless.

69
00:07:39,846 --> 00:07:41,767
That's a very regular one, the deathless.

70
00:07:43,435 --> 00:07:46,423
It is undefiled and it is sorrowless.

71
00:07:46,442 --> 00:07:49,471
There's no dukkha, there's no sorrow in Nibbana.

72
00:07:50,213 --> 00:07:58,778
So whatever is the cause of our unsatisfaction in today's life, that you will not find in Nibbana.

73
00:08:03,516 --> 00:08:15,949
Before my enlightenment, while I was still only an unenlightened bodhisattva, remember this word bodhisattva means someone seeking, in Theravada Buddhism it's someone who seeks full self-liberation.

74
00:08:19,033 --> 00:08:22,617
I too, being subject to birth, sought what was also subject to birth.

75
00:08:24,079 --> 00:08:32,206
And then he goes on and he says, and I considered thus, why, being myself subject to birth, do I seek what is also subject to birth?

76
00:08:32,591 --> 00:08:42,736
Why, being myself subject to aging, sickness, death, sorrow and defilement, do I seek that also which is subject to aging, sickness, death, sorrow and defilement?

77
00:08:43,392 --> 00:08:54,761
Suppose that being myself subject to birth, having understood the danger in what is subject to birth, I seek the unborn supreme security from Nibbana.

78
00:08:54,782 --> 00:09:13,399
Supposing that being myself subject to aging and sickness, death, sorrow and defilement, having understood the danger of what is subject to aging, sickness, death, sorrow and defilement, I seek the unaging, the unhailing, deathless, sorrowless and undefiled supreme security from bondage, Nibbana.

79
00:09:13,379 --> 00:09:24,961
Now this word, seeking from bondage, you see, one of the definitions of Nibbana, the words that make it up, is to be unshackled.

80
00:09:25,982 --> 00:09:26,604
Unshackled.

81
00:09:27,144 --> 00:09:31,253
And one of the things that you're liberated from are the ten fetters.

82
00:09:31,232 --> 00:09:58,961
so it's another way of describing Nibbana and he talks about the taste of Nibbana is what we read in our little verses here the taste of Nibbana is freedom is this unshackling freedom so now later while still a black haired young man endowed with the blessing of youth in the prime of life

83
00:09:59,498 --> 00:10:12,596
Though my mother and father wished otherwise and wept with tearful faces, I shaved off my hair and beard, put on the ochre robe and went forth from the home life into homelessness.

84
00:10:13,918 --> 00:10:15,620
So his mum and dad were really upset.

85
00:10:19,988 --> 00:10:21,590
There, of course, it says ochre robe.

86
00:10:21,789 --> 00:10:24,274
See, that again is an anachronism because

87
00:10:25,013 --> 00:10:37,885
At the first, he would just do what a lot of the ascetics at that time were doing, which was just picking up these rag robes from the charnel grounds, or any old robe, and just sewing it together in any bits and pieces.

88
00:10:37,905 --> 00:10:38,706
Anyway, you know.

89
00:10:38,726 --> 00:10:41,750
And it's interesting that in the West, we have the example of St. Francis.

90
00:10:41,831 --> 00:10:42,831
He did exactly the same.

91
00:10:42,871 --> 00:10:45,313
If you ever see his, he had a couple of robes.

92
00:10:45,354 --> 00:10:52,020
If you ever see his robe in Assisi, it's just a patchwork of sackcloth.

93
00:10:52,041 --> 00:10:52,741
Very inspiring.

94
00:10:55,337 --> 00:10:56,620
I suppose that's how bad it can get.

95
00:10:59,004 --> 00:11:01,870
Wait till the day of, never mind floods, wait till the day of doom.

96
00:11:02,270 --> 00:11:07,000
We'll all be out there collecting little bits of rags and trying to keep warm.

97
00:11:09,104 --> 00:11:18,020
Having gone forth, monks, in the search of what is wholesome, seeking the supreme state of sublime peace, I went to Alara Kalama and said to him, friend Kalama,

98
00:11:18,423 --> 00:11:21,687
I want to lead the spiritual life in this Dharma and discipline.

99
00:11:22,469 --> 00:11:32,403
Now, in those times, there were, of course, many teachers who had their own disciples and who taught a particular way of meditation, particular attainments.

100
00:11:33,164 --> 00:11:36,330
And here, all of them had a Dharma and a discipline.

101
00:11:36,669 --> 00:11:41,076
So the Dharma is the truth, the practice and the way of the truth.

102
00:11:41,356 --> 00:11:45,383
And the discipline was the rules and regulations to support it.

103
00:11:46,004 --> 00:11:47,485
And that's exactly what the Buddha said.

104
00:11:47,525 --> 00:11:47,907
He left.

105
00:11:48,427 --> 00:11:49,168
when he died.

106
00:11:49,207 --> 00:11:55,696
He said, I've left you the Dharma, the theory and the practice, and the Vinaya, and the rule, the Sila.

107
00:11:56,918 --> 00:12:00,623
And that's your institution, you see.

108
00:12:00,643 --> 00:12:03,586
And Alara Kalama replied, the Venerable One may stay here.

109
00:12:04,106 --> 00:12:12,357
This Dharma is such that a wise man can soon enter upon and dwell in it, realizing for himself through direct knowledge his own teacher's doctrine.

110
00:12:12,980 --> 00:12:14,761
I soon quickly learned the Dharma.

111
00:12:15,243 --> 00:12:23,191
As far as mere lip reciting and rehearsal of this teaching went, I could speak with knowledge and assurance and I claimed, I know and I see.

112
00:12:23,572 --> 00:12:24,952
And there were others who did likewise.

113
00:12:26,075 --> 00:12:35,966
And I considered, it is not through mere faith alone that Alara Kalama declares, by realizing it for himself with direct knowledge, I enter upon and dwell in the Dharma.

114
00:12:37,086 --> 00:12:40,029
Certainly Alara Kalama dwells knowing and seeing this Dharma.

115
00:12:40,650 --> 00:12:42,413
Then I went to Alara Kalama and asked him,

116
00:12:42,730 --> 00:12:52,764
Friend Kalama, in what way do you declare that by realizing it for yourself with direct knowledge you enter upon and dwell in this Dharma?

117
00:12:52,783 --> 00:12:58,432
And he replied, in reply he declared the base of nothingness.

118
00:12:58,993 --> 00:13:10,087
Now, you'll see here a distinction which the Buddha makes between knowing the Dharma as an intellectual understanding and actually realizing it for himself.

119
00:13:10,674 --> 00:13:16,083
And now he's asking Allah the Kalama, well, what is your realization?

120
00:13:16,304 --> 00:13:17,647
And he says it's the base of nothingness.

121
00:13:17,687 --> 00:13:19,210
In other words, what is your Nibbana?

122
00:13:19,450 --> 00:13:22,274
I mean, what is the point of this whole practice?

123
00:13:22,294 --> 00:13:29,047
Now, the base of nothingness is what we call one of the Arupajanas.

124
00:13:29,067 --> 00:13:33,595
So, the Arupajanas, these absorption states, these ecstasies,

125
00:13:34,115 --> 00:13:37,601
are based on something which is created by the mind.

126
00:13:37,761 --> 00:13:44,414
So it could be through a mantra, it could be through the breath, it could be through metta-bhauna.

127
00:13:45,798 --> 00:13:54,755
But then, and you can go right up with certain, not all of them, like you can't get the fourth jhana with something like metta because it's a feeling.

128
00:13:55,511 --> 00:13:59,697
But with the breath you can, you can attain this state of equanimity.

129
00:14:01,318 --> 00:14:04,884
Here meaning this absolute stillness of the mind, you see.

130
00:14:04,903 --> 00:14:12,133
But then there's a flip, and the mind, as it were, leaves the phenomenal life and enters into this other state called the arupajāna.

131
00:14:12,874 --> 00:14:22,667
And these arupajānas have the same quality, but within them there is a different perception, for want of a better word.

132
00:14:23,474 --> 00:14:36,249
So the first one is the perception of space and then the perception of consciousness, the perception of nothingness and the perception of neither perception nor not perception.

133
00:14:36,769 --> 00:14:45,499
So all these are sort of words you might say, but the point is that in that sort of realm of the mind,

134
00:14:45,918 --> 00:15:03,942
completely abstracted from the sensual world and from the perceptions and feelings of the sensual world created by the mind so the mind has now completely abstracted itself from connection with the world

135
00:15:04,565 --> 00:15:09,418
there is this state called the state of nothingness, which means that there's nothing in it.

136
00:15:09,840 --> 00:15:14,774
So it's like being conscious, being fully conscious with nothing in it.

137
00:15:15,073 --> 00:15:19,586
I mean, as a sort of...

138
00:15:19,567 --> 00:15:25,893
as a sort of image of that, being in a completely dark room and yet being awake, being conscious in it.

139
00:15:26,153 --> 00:15:27,554
You're not conscious of anything.

140
00:15:29,277 --> 00:15:33,341
So that was what he got to, this state of being.

141
00:15:33,701 --> 00:15:43,991
So I considered, not only Alara Kalama has faith, energy, mindfulness, concentration, wisdom, I too have faith, energy, mindfulness, concentration, wisdom.

142
00:15:44,251 --> 00:15:49,017
Suppose I endeavor to realize the Dhamma that Alara Kalama declares

143
00:15:49,350 --> 00:15:53,919
he enters upon and dwells in by realizing it for himself with direct knowledge.

144
00:15:54,561 --> 00:16:06,785
Now, you'll notice here that even at this stage, before he's fully liberated anything, he's saying that he was aware that you needed these five spiritual faculties, faith, energy, mindfulness.

145
00:16:07,221 --> 00:16:08,604
concentration of wisdom.

146
00:16:10,346 --> 00:16:12,750
So the faith, of course, is basic.

147
00:16:13,773 --> 00:16:20,985
Bhikkhu Bodhi translates it as faith, but that has all sorts of connotations for us in the West because of belief.

148
00:16:21,625 --> 00:16:31,542
It's more like confidence, a complete confidence in the teacher and in what he's suggesting that we can attain.

149
00:16:31,522 --> 00:16:37,970
The energy, of course, is the energy to be mindful and to continue with the investigation, or the practice, rather.

150
00:16:38,730 --> 00:16:42,095
And then there's the concentration, which is that steadiness of attention.

151
00:16:42,836 --> 00:16:44,136
It doesn't wander all over the place.

152
00:16:44,418 --> 00:16:52,246
So here already, he's suggesting that he understood what the five faculties, the five spiritual faculties were.

153
00:16:54,774 --> 00:17:01,206
I soon quickly entered upon and dwelled in that dharma by realizing it for myself with direct knowledge.

154
00:17:01,225 --> 00:17:10,741
Then I went to Alara Kalama and asked him, Friend Kalama, is it in this way that you declare that you enter upon and dwell in this dharma by realizing it for yourself with direct knowledge?

155
00:17:11,442 --> 00:17:12,545
This is the way, friend.

156
00:17:13,165 --> 00:17:20,377
It is in this way, friend, that I also enter upon and dwell in the dharma by realizing it for myself with direct knowledge.

157
00:17:21,116 --> 00:17:27,045
It is a gain for us, friend, it is a great gain for us that we have such a venerable one for our fellow monk.

158
00:17:27,726 --> 00:17:40,222
So the Dharma that I declare I enter upon and dwell in by realizing it for myself with direct knowledge is the Dharma that you enter upon and dwell in by realizing it for yourself with direct knowledge.

159
00:17:40,944 --> 00:17:54,047
And the Dharma that you enter upon and dwell in by realizing it for yourself with direct knowledge is the Dharma that I declare I enter upon and dwell in by realizing it for myself with direct knowledge.

160
00:17:54,627 --> 00:17:58,914
So you know the Dharma that I know and I know the Dharma that you know.

161
00:17:59,435 --> 00:18:00,778
As I am, so are you.

162
00:18:00,837 --> 00:18:02,842
As you are, so I am.

163
00:18:03,221 --> 00:18:06,548
Come friend, let us now lead this community together.

164
00:18:08,147 --> 00:18:15,296
Thus Alara Kalama, my teacher, placed me, his pupil, on an equal footing with himself and awarded me the greatest honor.

165
00:18:16,096 --> 00:18:30,534
But it occurred to me, the Dharma does not lead to disenchantment, to dispassion, to cessation, to peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to nibbana, but only to rebirth in the base of nothingness.

166
00:18:32,096 --> 00:18:36,500
Not being satisfied with that Dharma, disappointed with it, I left.

167
00:18:38,573 --> 00:18:56,768
So here, even though he attained this very high state of concentration, very high state of stillness, complete stillness in the base of nothingness, yet he realized that it was only going to produce more rebirth into this state.

168
00:18:57,440 --> 00:19:06,634
and therefore did not undermine his enchantment with life, his lack of being caught up in life, the dispassion.

169
00:19:07,454 --> 00:19:10,078
It wasn't a cessation of suffering.

170
00:19:10,138 --> 00:19:13,544
It wasn't going to bring an end to his unsatisfactoriness.

171
00:19:14,025 --> 00:19:15,346
It didn't lead to peace.

172
00:19:15,866 --> 00:19:25,862
And it wasn't a direct knowledge of enlightenment itself and therefore was not what he was really seeking, which he's already calling Nibbana.

173
00:19:25,882 --> 00:19:30,848
Even though if you remember, a lot of Kalama also thinks that he's also achieved Nibbana.

174
00:19:31,470 --> 00:19:34,034
But he now comes to the conclusion that he hasn't.

175
00:19:34,875 --> 00:19:41,924
And he says, not being satisfied with that Dharma, disappointed with it, I left.

176
00:19:43,778 --> 00:19:46,121
So I shall leave that for this evening.

177
00:19:46,461 --> 00:19:54,393
And if you come back next week, there's a very exciting installment when he meets Udaka Ramaputa.

178
00:19:55,253 --> 00:20:03,144
I can only hope that you have been greatly excited and drawn to deeper practice.

179
00:20:03,664 --> 00:20:12,317
May you be fully liberated from all suffering and not be confused by different Nibhanas sooner rather than later.

180
00:20:13,089 --> 00:20:18,105
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

